"""FAIM user guide (full How-To). Loaded by Guide Helper dialog."""

GUIDE_MARKDOWN = '## 🚀 Getting Started\n1. **Select Data Source**: \n   - **Last 30 Days (Quick)**: Sample data for testing\n   - **NASA POWER API (Full)**: Real NASA data\n   - **Forecasting**: ML-powered predictions with multiple advanced methods\n\n2. **Map Controls**:\n   - **Map Zoom Level Slider**: Fast zoom control (3-18) for all maps\n   - **Heatmap Opacity Slider**: Adjust transparency (0.1-1.0) for better blending with satellite imagery\n   - Higher opacity values (0.7-1.0) recommended for Detailed view with satellite imagery\n   - Lower opacity values (0.3-0.5) work well for Street/Terrain views\n\n3. **Select Map Type**:\n   - **Street**: Clean street map view (CartoDB Positron)\n   - **Terrain**: Detailed terrain view (OpenStreetMap)\n   - **Detailed**: Satellite imagery with buildings, trees, and labels (Esri World Imagery)\n   - Available for both Interactive Map and Spatial Distribution map\n   - Zoom in on Detailed view to see individual buildings and vegetation\n\n4. **For Forecasting Mode**:\n   - Set historical date range (60+ days recommended)\n   - **SELECT TARGET METRIC**: Choose which parameter to forecast\n   - **SELECT FEATURES**: Choose which metrics to use for training\n   - **Select All Features**: Checkbox to quickly select all available features\n   - Choose forecast methods (see sidebar for available options)\n   - Set forecast horizon (7 days to 2 years)\n   - Draw AOI and view Time Series to generate forecast\n\n## 🗺️ Smooth Blue Gradient Heatmaps\nAll spatial maps feature **smooth gradient visualization**:\n- **Flowing patterns** - Smooth, continuous heatmaps without blocky squares\n- **Blue gradient scale** - Professional single-color gradient from light to dark blue\n  - Light blue (#E3F2FD) = Low values\n  - Dark blue (#0D47A1) = High values\n- **Better map visibility** - Transparent overlay (30-70% opacity) lets you see streets, terrain, and features underneath\n- **Smooth blending** - High blur and radius create natural-looking patterns\n- **Dynamic legend** showing:\n  - Blue gradient color bar (matches actual map colors)\n  - Value range (min/max) for current view\n  - Mean and standard deviation\n- **Works at all zoom levels** - Consistent appearance whether zoomed in or out\n- Visible in all modes: Quick, API, and Forecasting\n\n## 🤖 Advanced Forecast Methods\n\n### Traditional ML Methods:\n- **Linear Regression**: Simple baseline model\n- **Random Forest**: Ensemble of decision trees (recommended default)\n- **Gradient Boosting**: Sequential ensemble method\n- **XGBoost**: Advanced gradient boosting with regularization\n- **FBLiR**: Fuzzy Bayesian Linear Regression - uncertainty-aware predictions\n\n### Time Series Specialists:\n- **Prophet**: Facebook\'s time series forecasting with automatic seasonality detection\n\n### Combined:\n- **Ensemble**: Averages predictions from all selected methods\n\n## 🎛️ FBLiR (Fuzzy Bayesian Linear Regression) Process\n\nFBLiR combines three powerful techniques to create robust, uncertainty-aware predictions:\n\n### How FBLiR Handles Seasonality:\n\nFBLiR captures seasonal patterns through multiple mechanisms:\n\n1. **Cyclical Feature Engineering**:\n   - Uses cos/sin transformations of temporal features\n   - These transformations preserve the circular nature of seasons\n   - Example: December (month 12) and January (month 1) are treated as adjacent months\n   - Without cos/sin: January=1, December=12 (large numerical gap)\n   - With cos/sin: Both map to similar points on a circle (continuous)\n\n2. **Historical Pattern Matching**:\n   - Looks back at same time of year from historical data\n   - Matches day-of-year ±7 days for seasonal context\n   - Ensures forecasts follow natural seasonal cycles\n   - Example: To forecast July temps, we reference historical July data\n\n3. **Fuzzy Seasonal Representation**:\n   - Fuzzification captures uncertainty in seasonal transitions\n   - Spring/Fall transitions are naturally fuzzy periods\n   - Model learns fuzzy boundaries between seasons\n\n4. **Multi-window Rolling Features**:\n   - 7-day, 14-day, and 30-day rolling averages\n   - Captures short, medium, and long-term seasonal trends\n   - Smooths out daily noise while preserving patterns\n\n**Why cos/sin Transformations Matter:**\n- Traditional encoding treats time as a straight line\n- December 31 → January 1 appears as a huge jump (365 → 1)\n- Cos/sin transforms create a continuous circle\n- Adjacent dates remain close in mathematical space\n- Result: Model understands seasonal continuity naturally\n\n### FBLiR Key Features:\n- Uses **Gaussian Fuzzy Numbers (GFN)** with mean and variance (not triangular/trapezoidal)\n- Based on Abdalla & Buckley 2007 GFN operations\n- Combines fuzzy logic, Bayesian inference, and linear regression\n- Provides uncertainty quantification (confidence intervals)\n- Automatic hyperparameter tuning\n- Good for noisy or imprecise data\n- Best for risk assessment scenarios\n- Note: Requires fuzzy_bayesian_regression_V3.py in app directory\n\n**Recommended combinations:**\n- Quick start: Random Forest only\n- Standard: Random Forest + XGBoost + Ensemble\n- Advanced: Random Forest + XGBoost + Prophet + Ensemble\n- Uncertainty-aware: FBLiR + Random Forest + Ensemble\n\n## 🌊 Seasonality in All Forecasts\nAll ML methods properly capture seasonality through:\n- Historical seasonal pattern matching - features look back at the same time of year\n- Day of year features (1-365)\n- Month indicators (1-12)\n- Day of week patterns\n- Rolling averages to maintain trends\n- Cos/sin transformations for cyclical continuity\n- Forecasts follow seasonal patterns from historical data\n- Result: Temperature, humidity, and other metrics follow their natural seasonal cycles\n\n## 🎯 Feature Selection\nChoose which metrics to use as features for training:\n- Select relevant meteorological parameters individually\n- Or use "Select All Features" checkbox for comprehensive training\n- System automatically creates lag features and rolling statistics\n- More relevant features = better predictions\n\n## 🔥 Fire Danger Indices\n\n### Fire Weather Index (FWI)\nCanadian-based index combining temperature, humidity, wind, and precipitation\n**Scale**: 0-25 (Low), 25-50 (Moderate), 50-75 (High), 75-100 (Extreme)\n\n### Australian Fire Danger Rating (AFDR)\nBased on McArthur FFDI with drought factor\n**Categories**: 🟢 Low-Moderate, 🟡 High, 🟠 Very High, 🔴 Severe, ⚫ Extreme\n\n## 💡 Tips\n- Use the **Zoom Slider** in sidebar for quick navigation\n- Blue gradient heatmaps provide better map visibility - darker blue = higher values\n- Check the **Dynamic Legend** to understand value ranges and the blue gradient scale\n- Use **Street view** for clean visualization and reports\n- Use **Terrain view** to understand landscape context\n- Use **Detailed view** to see exact structures at risk (zoom in!)\n- Smooth flowing heatmaps show patterns without blocking map features underneath\n- For best forecasts, use 90+ days of historical data\n- Use "Select All Features" for comprehensive model training\n- Try multiple methods and compare results\n- If you get "not enough data" error, try fewer features or longer historical period\n'
